WEBVTT

00:00.876 --> 00:03.626
This world may change...

00:04.588 --> 00:06.128
But that will never change.

00:07.007 --> 00:08.507
Must get a message
to Murtagh, then.

00:08.634 --> 00:09.804
If he can be warned,
maybe he can

00:09.885 --> 00:11.685
convince his men to retreat.

00:11.762 --> 00:13.352
I’ll deliver the message
to Murtagh.

00:13.472 --> 00:14.682
You cannot win.
You do not win.

00:14.765 --> 00:16.475
The history has been written.

00:16.558 --> 00:18.518
Then I do fight.

00:18.644 --> 00:20.314
Ye’re with the militia,
are ye?

00:20.395 --> 00:22.305
I came to warn you about Tryon.

00:22.397 --> 00:23.687
So ye’re a traitor.

00:23.774 --> 00:24.774
[ gunshot ]

00:24.858 --> 00:27.068
[ dramatic music ]

00:27.194 --> 00:28.864
[ grunting ]

00:28.987 --> 00:30.607
I released ye from yer oath.

00:30.697 --> 00:32.367
I’d never betray yer mother,

00:32.491 --> 00:34.031
no matter who asked.

00:34.159 --> 00:35.409
♪

00:35.536 --> 00:37.036
Murtagh?

00:37.162 --> 00:38.042
Roger?

00:38.163 --> 00:40.213
♪

00:40.290 --> 00:41.330
Bree.

00:46.672 --> 00:48.672
Fear not,
it’s not life or death.

00:49.550 --> 00:51.260
Just a bit of red pen...

00:51.385 --> 00:54.305
or is it, Mr. Jones?

00:54.388 --> 00:56.598
I’m sorry, sir?

00:56.723 --> 00:58.643
Is it life and death,
do you think?

00:58.725 --> 01:02.015
I...I don’t suppose so, sir.

01:02.104 --> 01:05.824
But I was wondering,
what does it mean

01:05.899 --> 01:10.239
when you write the term
so‐and‐so "was finally able
to bury the hatchet"?

01:10.320 --> 01:14.280
We all know that means
to make peace in some way,

01:14.408 --> 01:17.658
but can you tell me
why anyone would go

01:17.744 --> 01:19.254
to the trouble of burying one?

01:22.666 --> 01:24.246
Perhaps you should
just go, then.

01:25.419 --> 01:28.419
Unless you have any last words
for us before ye leave.

01:31.967 --> 01:35.347
"I came, I saw, I conquered."

01:35.429 --> 01:36.809
[ laughter ]

01:36.930 --> 01:39.930
Not quite what I’m looking for,
Mr. Morgan.

01:40.017 --> 01:42.557
And those were not
Caesar’s last words.

01:43.270 --> 01:44.690
Although he did meet
an unhappy end.

01:44.771 --> 01:45.981
Stay, Mr. Jones.

01:47.357 --> 01:50.397
I wanted to see
if you’d agree with me,

01:50.485 --> 01:54.025
because I do believe
it’s a question
of life and death.

01:54.114 --> 01:58.084
Your essays on famous
last words were forgettable.

01:58.160 --> 02:01.790
I wanted you to really think
about why

02:01.872 --> 02:04.332
people say what they say

02:04.458 --> 02:06.418
and perhaps to consider

02:06.501 --> 02:09.801
what your own final words
might be, given the chance.

02:11.632 --> 02:13.552
MORGAN:
What does it matter, sir?

02:13.634 --> 02:18.224
This is history,
not creative writing.

02:18.305 --> 02:21.935
Because people live and die
by their words.

02:22.017 --> 02:25.227
They shape our thoughts
and deeds.

02:25.312 --> 02:26.522
Often, they define us.

02:28.148 --> 02:31.398
Like bullets, once fired,

02:31.485 --> 02:33.195
well, we can’t take ’em back.

02:33.320 --> 02:34.650
They have impact,

02:34.738 --> 02:37.658
so choose them wisely.

02:37.741 --> 02:39.661
Make them meaningful.

02:39.785 --> 02:42.625
Live a life worthy of them...

02:42.704 --> 02:44.504
especially your last words.

02:44.581 --> 02:46.121
They outlive us.

02:47.501 --> 02:49.251
And what will yours be, sir?

02:56.259 --> 02:59.299
It is my dying wish,
O Lord...

02:59.388 --> 03:01.348
that my students write
structured arguments...

03:01.473 --> 03:03.313
[ laughter ]

03:03.392 --> 03:07.402
Supported by evidence
and legible handwriting, amen.

03:07.521 --> 03:10.191
No, really, sir.

03:14.194 --> 03:16.244
I’d say...

03:16.363 --> 03:18.073
[ clears throat ]

03:21.952 --> 03:24.042
I’d say let history
forget my name...

03:26.623 --> 03:30.593
So long as my words
and my deeds

03:30.711 --> 03:32.961
are remembered
by those I love.

03:37.050 --> 03:38.720
That’s all for today.

03:38.844 --> 03:40.224
Until next week.

03:47.060 --> 03:48.900
You’re early.

03:49.020 --> 03:50.770
Couldn’t resist the chance
to see you in action.

03:50.897 --> 03:52.437
And if you wanna make
The Great Train Robbery,

03:52.566 --> 03:53.606
we need to get a move on.

03:53.734 --> 03:54.904
Yeah, are you sure
you’re all right

03:54.985 --> 03:56.695
with a silent movie marathon?

03:56.778 --> 03:58.778
You aren’t just humoring me?

03:58.905 --> 04:00.275
No, I am.

04:00.407 --> 04:01.867
[ chuckles ]

04:01.950 --> 04:03.870
But you suffered
through an entire lecture

04:03.952 --> 04:05.332
about suspension bridges.

04:05.412 --> 04:07.412
So fair is fair.

04:18.383 --> 04:20.263
Would those really be
your last words?

04:27.267 --> 04:29.637
CHOIR:
♪ Sing me a song ♪

04:29.770 --> 04:32.770
♪ Of a lass that is gone ♪

04:32.898 --> 04:34.898
♪ Say, could that lass ♪

04:34.983 --> 04:38.113
♪ Be I? ♪

04:38.195 --> 04:40.495
♪ Merry of soul ♪

04:40.614 --> 04:43.494
♪ She sailed on a day ♪

04:43.617 --> 04:45.617
♪ Over the sea ♪

04:45.702 --> 04:48.622
♪ To Skye ♪

04:48.705 --> 04:51.165
♪ Billow and breeze ♪

04:51.291 --> 04:54.001
♪ Islands and seas ♪

04:54.127 --> 04:56.957
♪ Mountains of rain and sun ♪

04:57.047 --> 04:59.507
♪ Mountains of rain
and sun ♪

04:59.633 --> 05:01.633
♪ All that was good ♪

05:01.760 --> 05:04.100
♪ All that was fair ♪

05:04.179 --> 05:06.639
♪ All that was me ♪

05:06.765 --> 05:09.605
♪ Is gone ♪

05:09.684 --> 05:11.814
♪ Sing me a song ♪

05:11.937 --> 05:14.687
♪ Of a lass that is gone ♪

05:14.815 --> 05:16.825
♪ Say, could that lass ♪

05:16.900 --> 05:19.940
♪ Be I? ♪

05:20.028 --> 05:22.068
♪ Merry of soul ♪

05:22.155 --> 05:24.945
♪ She sailed on a day ♪

05:25.033 --> 05:29.663
♪ Over the sea ♪

05:29.788 --> 05:35.668
♪ To Skye ♪

05:35.794 --> 05:38.634
[ dramatic music ]

05:38.713 --> 05:41.633
♪

05:48.557 --> 05:51.017
[ projector whirring ]

07:23.777 --> 07:24.777
[ projector stops ]

07:37.958 --> 07:39.668
CLAIRE:
Everything looks good.

07:39.793 --> 07:42.753
Your throat’s healing nicely.
Scar’s faded.

07:47.175 --> 07:48.625
How do you feel?

07:52.514 --> 07:55.144
You really should try
to speak, Roger.

07:57.978 --> 08:00.808
It’ll sound croaky at first,
but it’s perfectly normal.

08:06.069 --> 08:07.609
BRIANNA:
Maybe just try to whisper.

08:12.659 --> 08:15.079
All right, well...

08:15.161 --> 08:17.831
just know that I’ll be
teaching Jem to say

08:17.956 --> 08:20.036
"sweater" and "aluminum."

08:20.166 --> 08:22.496
It’s not gonna be "jumper"
or "aluminium."

08:29.134 --> 08:32.014
70% of communication
is nonverbal.

08:32.095 --> 08:33.855
Who needs words anyway?

08:35.682 --> 08:37.392
We can pretend we’re in one
of those silent movies

08:37.517 --> 08:40.387
we used to go and see
in Oxford or Kenmore Square.

08:43.398 --> 08:45.268
CLAIRE:
Lord John has brought
a‐a whole trunk

08:45.358 --> 08:47.238
of books and gifts.

08:47.360 --> 08:48.900
Would you like to come up
to the house to see him?

08:50.864 --> 08:52.624
BRIANNA:
All right, well...

08:52.699 --> 08:54.159
I’ll go with you.

09:02.000 --> 09:04.250
[ door clicks shut ]

09:05.795 --> 09:07.835
[ footsteps departing ]

09:09.382 --> 09:12.592
[ clearing throat ]

09:12.719 --> 09:15.559
[ ominous music ]

09:15.680 --> 09:18.560
♪

09:24.898 --> 09:27.318
BUCK:
Coward, whichever way
you look at it.

09:30.737 --> 09:31.737
[ squeaks ]

09:33.281 --> 09:35.071
[ exhales sharply ]

09:35.158 --> 09:37.948
[ projector whirring ]

10:31.214 --> 10:32.764
[ exhales sharply ]

10:32.841 --> 10:35.641
[ soft dramatic music ]

10:35.760 --> 10:38.180
♪

10:38.304 --> 10:39.814
[ sighs ]

10:39.889 --> 10:42.809
♪

10:48.356 --> 10:52.776
BRIANNA:
My roommate from MIT, Gayle...

10:52.861 --> 10:55.031
she had this boyfriend
who went to Vietnam.

10:56.573 --> 10:59.123
I didn’t really know him
all that well, but...

10:59.200 --> 11:02.370
she asked me to go with her
to see him a few times
after he got back.

11:04.998 --> 11:08.248
He’d been back almost a year
when I first went.

11:08.334 --> 11:10.884
I don’t really know
what I was expecting, but...

11:12.380 --> 11:13.710
He was like a zombie...

11:13.840 --> 11:16.180
[ somber music ]

11:16.301 --> 11:18.551
Just no life in his eyes
at all.

11:18.678 --> 11:20.548
♪

11:20.680 --> 11:23.680
Gayle called it
his "thousand‐yard stare."

11:23.808 --> 11:25.848
♪

11:25.977 --> 11:28.097
He was hit by some shrapnel,

11:28.188 --> 11:29.768
but he wasn’t
seriously injured.

11:29.856 --> 11:32.186
♪

11:32.275 --> 11:35.535
Yeah, we would call that
"war neurosis."

11:36.988 --> 11:38.858
Shell shock.

11:38.948 --> 11:40.368
♪

11:40.450 --> 11:42.830
It’s been months now,

11:42.911 --> 11:45.081
and you said that Roger
is physically fine.

11:46.456 --> 11:49.576
So maybe it is war neurosis.

11:51.252 --> 11:53.302
I mean, it must be mental...

11:53.379 --> 11:54.839
psychological...

11:56.633 --> 11:58.263
It’s like he’s drowning
in silence.

11:58.384 --> 12:00.934
♪

12:01.054 --> 12:04.684
And he has that same
thousand‐yard stare
in his eyes.

12:04.766 --> 12:07.686
♪

12:09.604 --> 12:11.904
I’m afraid he’s lost.

12:11.981 --> 12:14.401
♪

12:14.484 --> 12:18.494
No matter how lost he is...

12:18.571 --> 12:22.911
you just have to have faith
that you find him.

12:22.992 --> 12:25.872
♪

12:33.253 --> 12:35.923
JOCASTA:
♪ There’ll be
nae more liltin’ ♪

12:37.757 --> 12:42.087
♪ Nae laughin’ or kissin’ ♪

12:43.596 --> 12:48.426
♪ Go in peace and ♪

12:48.559 --> 12:51.979
♪ Leave us to grieve ♪

12:54.607 --> 12:57.687
♪ Sighin’ and moanin’ ♪

12:59.612 --> 13:05.122
♪ On ilka green loanin’ ♪

13:07.161 --> 13:11.621
♪ The flowers of the forest ♪

13:12.667 --> 13:16.837
♪ Are all wede away ♪

13:28.683 --> 13:31.693
[ footsteps approaching ]

13:36.065 --> 13:39.605
I thought perhaps I could have
had a headstone made for him.

13:39.694 --> 13:42.244
I ken ’tis no’ my place.

13:42.322 --> 13:45.492
Murtagh and I were not
husband and wife.

13:45.616 --> 13:49.496
Neither were we
father and son, but...

13:49.579 --> 13:50.999
it doesna make
the pain any less...

13:53.291 --> 13:55.081
Or easier to bear.

14:00.590 --> 14:02.590
He was as stubborn
as yer father.

14:03.885 --> 14:05.725
If only he’d stayed
by your side.

14:07.513 --> 14:08.683
He did.

14:10.516 --> 14:14.476
He kept his vow to me...
to my mother.

14:19.442 --> 14:21.112
He was loyal above all.

14:22.528 --> 14:24.108
We canna fault him for that.

14:27.700 --> 14:29.870
Your carriage awaits, Mistress.

14:31.662 --> 14:34.422
[ solemn string music ]

14:34.540 --> 14:36.830
♪

14:36.918 --> 14:39.878
Ye’ll give my thanks
to Claire once more.

14:40.004 --> 14:41.094
Aye.

14:41.214 --> 14:44.094
♪

14:46.260 --> 14:47.800
Well...

14:49.055 --> 14:50.395
Good‐bye, Auntie.

14:50.473 --> 14:53.273
♪

14:56.521 --> 14:59.151
How careful we’d be if we kent

14:59.232 --> 15:01.322
which good‐byes were our last.

15:01.401 --> 15:04.241
♪

15:04.320 --> 15:07.110
[ birds chirping ]

15:07.240 --> 15:09.910
♪

15:49.031 --> 15:50.161
[ sighs ]

15:50.283 --> 15:53.163
♪

15:58.624 --> 16:02.634
"I offer my apologies
for the injury done
to your son‐in‐law.

16:02.712 --> 16:04.132
It was
a most regrettable error."

16:09.719 --> 16:11.679
Governor Tryon
has granted Roger

16:11.804 --> 16:13.684
5,000 acres in the backcountry.

16:13.806 --> 16:15.676
What?
Why?

16:17.143 --> 16:18.063
Compensation.

16:19.896 --> 16:22.686
Or perhaps he thinks
he can buy your forgiveness.

16:23.566 --> 16:25.776
And what will we do
with 5,000 acres?

16:25.860 --> 16:28.360
It won’t undo
what’s happened to Roger...

16:28.488 --> 16:30.198
but it’s a valuable tract
of land.

16:30.323 --> 16:32.623
Tryon can keep his land.
I don’t need land.

16:32.700 --> 16:34.160
I need my husband back.

16:46.589 --> 16:47.839
[ clears throat ]

16:54.347 --> 16:55.307
[ sniffles ]

16:59.727 --> 17:02.557
[ foreboding music ]

17:02.688 --> 17:05.438
♪

17:05.525 --> 17:09.245
[ breathing shakily ]

17:09.362 --> 17:12.162
[ projector whirring ]

18:06.669 --> 18:08.249
[ exhales sharply ]

18:08.379 --> 18:09.589
[ sharp bang ]

18:09.714 --> 18:12.764
[ muffled voices, sharp bang ]

18:12.883 --> 18:15.893
[ breathing heavily ]

18:30.693 --> 18:32.783
I brought something...

18:32.862 --> 18:34.282
something that always
made me feel as though

18:34.405 --> 18:37.495
I had the wisdom of the heavens
in the palm of my hand.

18:38.618 --> 18:41.658
The astrolabe is, in many ways,
a model of the universe,

18:41.787 --> 18:43.957
an instrument you can use
to find your position,

18:44.040 --> 18:46.170
whether on land or at sea.

18:46.292 --> 18:48.592
You can even use it
to tell the time.

18:48.669 --> 18:50.799
To find our place in the world?

18:50.921 --> 18:53.471
Perhaps we should start
with something small.

18:53.549 --> 18:54.799
How ’bout telling the time?

18:54.925 --> 18:56.425
[ soft string music ]

18:56.510 --> 18:57.430
So...

18:57.511 --> 18:58.931
♪

18:59.013 --> 19:01.473
If the sun was there...

19:01.599 --> 19:03.309
that would mean...

19:03.392 --> 19:06.312
♪

19:11.150 --> 19:12.360
5:30.

19:12.485 --> 19:15.325
♪

19:15.404 --> 19:16.824
5:35.

19:16.906 --> 19:19.116
[ sighs ]

19:19.200 --> 19:22.120
Well, I guess we don’t have
all the answers.

19:23.537 --> 19:24.537
No.

19:26.832 --> 19:29.252
Sometimes
we must have patience.

19:29.335 --> 19:31.175
♪

19:31.253 --> 19:32.053
Thank you, John.

19:32.171 --> 19:35.091
♪

20:04.620 --> 20:06.870
[ grunts softly ]

20:06.997 --> 20:09.537
Glad to see you’ve found a way
to distract yourself.

20:09.625 --> 20:10.875
[ exhales sharply ]

20:13.045 --> 20:15.705
Been a difficult few months.

20:15.798 --> 20:18.378
[ dramatic music ]

20:18.467 --> 20:20.757
Is there a medicine for grief
in your time?

20:20.886 --> 20:22.796
♪

20:22.888 --> 20:25.718
Some of yer
wee invisible beasties

20:25.850 --> 20:27.390
to gnaw away at it?

20:27.476 --> 20:30.266
♪

20:30.396 --> 20:32.186
Unfortunately not.

20:32.273 --> 20:34.943
♪

20:35.067 --> 20:37.237
I don’t think there’ll
ever be a cure for that.

20:37.361 --> 20:39.401
♪

20:39.530 --> 20:41.110
Except maybe time.

20:41.240 --> 20:42.660
[ scoffs ]

20:43.492 --> 20:46.332
Well, they say time
heals all wounds.

20:46.412 --> 20:49.332
♪

20:57.214 --> 21:00.134
[ uplifting orchestral music ]

21:00.259 --> 21:03.139
♪

21:13.022 --> 21:16.022
[ chickens clucking ]

21:17.568 --> 21:19.148
[ pounding ]

21:19.278 --> 21:20.358
Hello?

21:21.614 --> 21:23.124
[ pounding ]

21:24.909 --> 21:25.829
‐ Hey.
‐ [ pounding ]

21:25.951 --> 21:27.951
What on earth is Roger doing?

21:28.078 --> 21:30.788
He is working on the stairs
for the loft.

21:30.873 --> 21:34.843
D’ye think he might stop
for a wee while?

21:34.960 --> 21:36.960
[ laughs ]
We brought you some leftovers.

21:37.046 --> 21:40.796
See if I can pry him away
from his newfound passion
for woodwork.

21:40.925 --> 21:43.395
[ pounding ]

21:43.469 --> 21:46.259
[ utensils clinking ]

21:47.765 --> 21:49.985
[ tapping ]

21:50.059 --> 21:51.769
Careful now,
[ speaking Gaelic ].

21:51.852 --> 21:53.652
[ tapping ]

21:53.771 --> 21:55.811
[ speaking Gaelic ]

21:55.898 --> 21:56.938
That’s a new one.

21:57.024 --> 21:59.074
Aye, it means "my blood."

21:59.151 --> 22:01.321
CLAIRE:
Thought that was
[ speaking Gaelic ].

22:01.403 --> 22:05.323
Aye, it is, but that’s
blood that comes out
when ye wound yerself.

22:05.449 --> 22:08.239
[ speaking Gaelic ]
is something you say
to a bairn, mostly...

22:08.327 --> 22:09.997
One ye’re related to,
of course.

22:10.079 --> 22:11.409
It’s lovely.

22:11.497 --> 22:13.577
[ kettle whistling ]

22:13.666 --> 22:14.666
Tea’s ready.

22:19.839 --> 22:21.339
Stop!

22:22.174 --> 22:24.594
[ Jemmy crying ]

22:24.677 --> 22:25.587
It’s okay.

22:25.678 --> 22:27.508
[ crying ]

22:32.810 --> 22:35.850
Oh, darling.
Jamie.

22:35.938 --> 22:37.188
[ crying continues ]

22:37.273 --> 22:38.823
Roger.

22:38.899 --> 22:41.149
Roger, you spoke.

22:41.235 --> 22:43.365
Can you ge‐can you say
something else?

22:44.780 --> 22:45.950
Does it hurt?

22:46.031 --> 22:47.451
Can you just try?

22:49.034 --> 22:50.084
[ whispering ]
Try for me.

22:50.202 --> 22:53.252
[ tense music ]

22:53.372 --> 22:56.212
♪

23:03.048 --> 23:04.218
[ saw buzzing ]

23:04.341 --> 23:05.681
BRIANNA:
♪ Oh, my darling ♪

23:05.759 --> 23:07.179
♪ Oh, my darling ♪

23:07.261 --> 23:10.061
♪ Oh, my darling Clementine ♪

23:10.180 --> 23:13.060
♪ You were lost
and gone forever ♪

23:13.142 --> 23:15.942
♪ Dreadful sorry, Clementine ♪

23:16.061 --> 23:19.061
♪ In a cavern, in a canyon ♪

23:19.148 --> 23:21.858
♪ Excavating for a mine ♪

23:21.942 --> 23:24.822
♪ Dwelt a miner forty‐niner ♪

23:24.904 --> 23:27.324
♪ And his daughter,
Clementine ♪

23:27.406 --> 23:30.076
♪ Oh, my darling,
oh, my darling ♪

23:30.159 --> 23:32.789
♪ Oh, my darling Clementine ♪

23:32.912 --> 23:35.752
♪ You were lost
and gone forever ♪

23:35.831 --> 23:38.751
♪ Dreadful sorry, Clementine ♪

23:38.876 --> 23:41.746
♪ She was light
and like a fairy ♪

23:41.879 --> 23:44.259
♪ And her shoes
were number nine ♪

23:44.340 --> 23:47.090
♪ Herring boxes
without topses ♪

23:47.217 --> 23:49.467
♪ Sandals were for Clementine ♪

23:49.595 --> 23:51.105
‐ [ pounding ]
‐ BRIANNA: ♪ Oh, my darling ♪

23:51.221 --> 23:52.811
♪ Oh, my darling ♪

23:52.932 --> 23:55.142
♪ Oh, my darling Clementine ♪

23:55.267 --> 23:58.977
♪ You were lost
and gone forever ♪

23:59.104 --> 24:01.484
♪ Dreadful sorry,
Clementine ♪

24:01.607 --> 24:04.107
[ crying ]

24:04.234 --> 24:07.864
JEMMY: One, two, three,
four, five, six...

24:07.947 --> 24:09.987
BOTH: Seven, eight,
nine, ten.

24:10.115 --> 24:11.825
[ gasps ]
Let’s find Grand‐da.

24:11.951 --> 24:13.411
‐ Find Grand‐da.
‐ [ Jemmy cooing ]

24:13.494 --> 24:15.294
‐ Ah! Yeah, ye found me!
‐ [ Claire laughs ]

24:15.371 --> 24:17.331
Yay!
Should we do it one more time?

24:17.456 --> 24:21.626
One, two, three, four,
five, six,

24:21.710 --> 24:23.550
seven, eight, nine, ten.

24:23.629 --> 24:26.009
[ animal growling ]

24:26.131 --> 24:28.881
Claire, take Jemmy
and go to the cabin.

24:28.968 --> 24:31.138
‐ [ growling continues ]
‐ Now.

24:31.261 --> 24:32.551
[ suspenseful music ]

24:32.638 --> 24:36.018
[ snarling ]

24:36.141 --> 24:37.771
[ squeals, body thuds ]

24:37.851 --> 24:39.981
♪

24:40.062 --> 24:43.772
[ panting ]

24:43.857 --> 24:46.817
♪

24:46.902 --> 24:48.902
[ dog barks ]

24:48.988 --> 24:52.158
♪

24:55.327 --> 24:57.997
[ dog barks ]

24:58.080 --> 25:00.830
Christ.
It’s Ian.

25:00.958 --> 25:03.208
[ emotional music ]

25:04.128 --> 25:05.338
CLAIRE: Ian!

25:05.462 --> 25:07.802
We thought we’d never
see you again.

25:07.881 --> 25:10.011
♪

25:10.092 --> 25:11.892
Will anyone be coming
after ye, lad?

25:13.429 --> 25:15.219
Not unless he has
any vengeful kin.

25:16.306 --> 25:17.846
Oh, we’ll eat well tonight...

25:17.975 --> 25:19.105
[ Claire chuckles ]

25:19.184 --> 25:20.564
In celebration.

25:20.686 --> 25:21.806
[ chuckles ]

25:21.895 --> 25:24.555
♪

25:34.825 --> 25:37.375
Bree, Roger!

25:37.453 --> 25:39.043
‐ [ Jemmy giggles ]
‐ [ door clatters open ]

25:39.163 --> 25:41.963
[ sentimental music ]

25:42.041 --> 25:45.171
♪

26:42.851 --> 26:43.771
[ sighs ]

26:43.852 --> 26:46.732
♪

26:52.611 --> 26:54.651
It is really good to see you.

26:56.865 --> 26:57.905
Aye.

26:57.991 --> 27:01.041
♪

27:01.120 --> 27:03.910
[ insects chirping ]

27:03.997 --> 27:06.957
♪

27:10.796 --> 27:12.956
JAMIE:
Well, lad, what d’ye think?

27:14.174 --> 27:17.974
It’s...big.

27:18.053 --> 27:19.603
[ chuckles ]

27:19.680 --> 27:21.140
JAMIE:
A lot of work went into it.

27:21.223 --> 27:23.143
Blood, sweat, and tears.

27:23.267 --> 27:25.267
Thankfully,
all the settlers helped.

27:27.312 --> 27:30.192
I can butcher the boar for us,
if ye’d like.

27:30.315 --> 27:32.355
Ian, you just got here.

27:32.484 --> 27:34.404
Don’t you want to settle in?

27:34.486 --> 27:36.696
Ye must be hungry.
I’ll have one of the men do it.

27:36.822 --> 27:38.202
Or Marsali.

27:38.323 --> 27:40.033
You should see her
wi’ a knife.

27:40.159 --> 27:42.789
I killed him.
I’ll do the butchering.

27:44.329 --> 27:46.999
Of course,
whatever you like.

27:48.167 --> 27:50.127
Come.

27:50.210 --> 27:52.550
[ solemn music ]

27:52.671 --> 27:54.841
D’ye mind if I stay outside
a bit longer?

27:54.923 --> 27:58.013
♪

27:58.093 --> 27:59.843
Make yerself at home, lad.

27:59.928 --> 28:02.808
♪

28:23.535 --> 28:25.865
[ cards flipping ]

28:25.954 --> 28:28.424
MARSALI:
What does my future hold?

28:34.087 --> 28:36.967
[ laughs ]

28:38.550 --> 28:40.050
That one’s called the lover.

28:41.511 --> 28:45.561
How many bairns
is too many, Fergus Fraser?

28:47.059 --> 28:48.939
[ sighs ]

28:49.061 --> 28:51.691
For Roger MacKenzie now.

28:54.900 --> 28:57.190
[ eerie music ]

28:57.277 --> 28:58.277
The hanged man.

28:58.403 --> 29:00.033
[ gasps ]

29:00.113 --> 29:00.913
[ laughs uncomfortably ]

29:00.989 --> 29:03.909
♪

29:28.183 --> 29:29.063
[ softly ]
Uh...

29:29.142 --> 29:32.062
♪

29:32.145 --> 29:34.435
Um...

29:34.564 --> 29:35.944
it was my mistake.

29:36.024 --> 29:37.784
♪

29:37.859 --> 29:39.029
We’ll try again.

29:39.111 --> 29:41.111
Let’s‐let’s try again,
Roger.

29:42.322 --> 29:43.662
[ clears throat ]

29:43.782 --> 29:46.622
♪

29:49.538 --> 29:52.538
[ projector whirring ]

29:54.960 --> 29:56.540
[ sharp bang ]

30:05.512 --> 30:06.472
[ grunts softly ]

30:06.555 --> 30:08.475
[ door clicks open ]

30:08.557 --> 30:09.767
What’s the matter?

30:09.850 --> 30:12.480
[ somber music ]

30:13.353 --> 30:15.313
What’s this?

30:15.439 --> 30:16.979
Nothing.

30:18.233 --> 30:19.823
Just a bit of harmless fun.

30:19.943 --> 30:22.823
♪

30:25.824 --> 30:27.164
[ sighs ]

30:27.284 --> 30:30.164
♪

30:33.707 --> 30:35.327
They are just cards,
you know.

30:35.417 --> 30:38.167
♪

30:38.253 --> 30:39.843
Talk to me, Roger.

30:39.963 --> 30:42.223
♪

30:42.341 --> 30:44.551
It doesn’t matter to me
how you sound.

30:44.676 --> 30:47.176
I know this is hard.

30:47.262 --> 30:50.142
Your voice, it’s...

30:50.223 --> 30:51.353
your gift.

30:51.433 --> 30:53.353
♪

30:53.435 --> 30:55.105
But you’re still you.

30:55.187 --> 30:58.267
You’re still the man I married,
and I want him back.

30:58.357 --> 31:00.067
Please.

31:00.192 --> 31:03.282
♪

31:03.362 --> 31:04.902
It’s not even
that you won’t talk.

31:05.030 --> 31:06.530
You won’t engage.

31:06.656 --> 31:09.696
I know how badly
you were hurt...

31:09.785 --> 31:12.165
‐ [ Roger sniffles ]
‐ And how scared
you must have been.

31:12.788 --> 31:15.158
But I went through
something awful too,

31:15.248 --> 31:18.168
something dark and ugly.

31:18.251 --> 31:21.251
And believe me,
all I wanted to do

31:21.380 --> 31:23.760
was to crawl
into a hole and die,

31:23.882 --> 31:26.052
and sometimes I still do.

31:26.134 --> 31:28.394
♪

31:28.470 --> 31:31.430
But I didn’t, and I don’t,

31:31.556 --> 31:35.476
because I have a husband
and a son who need me!

31:35.560 --> 31:37.770
I fought for us!

31:39.064 --> 31:41.864
And now I need...

31:41.942 --> 31:43.862
I need you.

31:43.944 --> 31:45.404
♪

31:45.487 --> 31:48.197
Jemmy needs you.

31:48.281 --> 31:51.161
♪

31:57.082 --> 32:00.252
I have been...patient.

32:00.377 --> 32:03.247
♪

32:06.508 --> 32:08.258
But I need to know...

32:08.385 --> 32:10.185
♪

32:10.262 --> 32:13.262
I need to know that you

32:13.348 --> 32:15.928
are not lost and gone forever.

32:17.102 --> 32:18.942
Are you coming back?

32:19.062 --> 32:22.192
♪

32:22.274 --> 32:26.364
Are you going to fight for us?

32:26.445 --> 32:29.325
♪

32:52.637 --> 32:54.807
I made you some special
almond hog’s pudding.

32:54.890 --> 32:56.980
I remember it’s one
of yer favorites.

32:57.058 --> 32:58.138
It is.

32:58.268 --> 32:59.808
[ dishes clink ]

32:59.895 --> 33:02.815
I thank ye, Lizzie.

33:10.363 --> 33:11.663
Lord...

33:12.782 --> 33:15.162
We thank ye for this meal...

33:15.285 --> 33:16.705
but above all,

33:16.828 --> 33:19.868
We thank ye for bringing
Young Ian home to us.

33:23.376 --> 33:24.496
CLAIRE:
Amen.

33:24.586 --> 33:25.546
BRIANNA:
Amen.

33:25.670 --> 33:26.800
JAMIE:
Amen.

33:35.680 --> 33:37.850
What a tale you must have
to tell.

33:37.933 --> 33:40.643
Start at the beginning,
and don’t leave anything out.

33:43.438 --> 33:46.018
Ye already ken
the beginning...

33:46.149 --> 33:49.029
and we’re eating
the ending for supper.

33:49.110 --> 33:51.950
MARSALI:
What about the‐the in‐between?

33:52.030 --> 33:53.410
Were the Mohawk good to ye?

33:56.201 --> 33:57.331
What were they like?

34:01.039 --> 34:04.079
They were...

34:04.209 --> 34:05.459
good people.

34:05.544 --> 34:06.964
Hmm.

34:10.215 --> 34:11.885
[ knife scraping ]

34:14.886 --> 34:15.926
[ clears throat ]

34:22.978 --> 34:25.098
Do you have plans
to return north?

34:27.774 --> 34:29.154
Back to the Mohawk?

34:33.989 --> 34:35.239
No.

34:40.161 --> 34:43.251
Bree, have ye, uh,
discussed the new land deed

34:43.373 --> 34:44.583
from Governor Tryon?

34:44.708 --> 34:47.918
We’re, um,
thinking about it.

34:48.003 --> 34:50.423
If we’re to hold on
to this land...

34:50.505 --> 34:52.715
we need to have it properly
surveyed and registered.

34:52.799 --> 34:55.339
I’m not sure Roger
is able to take on

34:55.427 --> 34:56.757
something like that
just yet.

34:58.263 --> 34:59.973
Maybe we can send
one of the men.

35:00.974 --> 35:03.434
If Myers wasn’t away trading...

35:07.939 --> 35:10.439
Maybe Ian will be willing
to go wi’ him.

35:11.693 --> 35:13.363
Ye ken how it’s done, lad?

35:13.445 --> 35:15.405
Ye helped us mark out
our boundaries at the Ridge

35:15.488 --> 35:16.948
when we first came.

35:17.032 --> 35:18.622
Will ye do this
for yer cousin?

35:18.742 --> 35:20.082
It’d...

35:20.160 --> 35:23.120
be a great help
to Roger and to us.

35:30.462 --> 35:32.342
Let’s give him some time
to think about it.

35:34.090 --> 35:35.760
‐Aye.
‐CLAIRE: Unfortunately,

35:35.842 --> 35:38.802
our guest chambers
aren’t ready upstairs yet,

35:38.887 --> 35:40.807
but you’re welcome
to the bed in the kitchen.

35:43.767 --> 35:45.057
Thank ye.

35:58.615 --> 35:59.745
[ insects chirping ]

35:59.824 --> 36:02.544
[ soft guitar music playing ]

36:02.661 --> 36:05.791
♪

36:12.629 --> 36:13.879
[ music stops ]

36:14.005 --> 36:16.375
[ ominous music ]

36:16.508 --> 36:17.468
[ projector whirs ]

36:17.550 --> 36:19.180
[ gulps ]

36:23.848 --> 36:27.058
[ whispering ]
♪ In a cavern, a canyon ♪

36:27.185 --> 36:30.685
♪ Excavating for a mine ♪

36:30.814 --> 36:34.654
♪ Dwelt a miner forty‐niner ♪

36:34.734 --> 36:36.364
[ sharp bang ]

36:36.444 --> 36:39.364
♪

36:39.489 --> 36:42.029
[ sharp bang ]

36:50.542 --> 36:53.382
[ solemn music ]

36:53.461 --> 36:56.381
♪

37:15.400 --> 37:18.240
[ Jamie coughs ]

37:19.571 --> 37:20.401
[ door clicks shut ]

37:21.740 --> 37:22.910
Ian.

37:24.242 --> 37:25.832
Lad...

37:25.910 --> 37:27.580
what are ye doing out here?

37:29.539 --> 37:30.409
I couldna sleep.

37:31.750 --> 37:33.080
Is the bed not to your liking?

37:35.754 --> 37:37.054
I’ve not been used
to having a bed

37:37.130 --> 37:39.090
in a house
this grand, Uncle.

37:39.174 --> 37:40.424
Aye.

37:47.265 --> 37:49.225
We, uh...

37:49.309 --> 37:50.979
we’re overjoyed
to have ye back.

37:53.104 --> 37:54.524
But ye seem out of sorts.

37:57.150 --> 37:58.610
Ye’re not yerself.

38:07.452 --> 38:09.202
What happened
with the Mohawk, lad?

38:10.789 --> 38:12.289
Ye can talk to me about it
if ye like.

38:15.794 --> 38:17.254
I canna give ye
the truth of it now.

38:19.172 --> 38:20.512
I dinna have the words.

38:24.135 --> 38:27.635
But there are things ye keep
hidden from others...

38:27.764 --> 38:29.144
ye and Claire both.

38:30.475 --> 38:33.275
[ dramatic music ]

38:33.353 --> 38:35.523
♪

38:35.647 --> 38:36.857
Aye.

38:36.981 --> 38:40.071
♪

38:46.783 --> 38:48.333
I understand.

38:48.451 --> 38:51.331
♪

38:53.456 --> 38:56.036
It makes me heartsick
to see ye troubled so.

38:57.836 --> 38:59.496
Ye need no’ worry for me.

38:59.587 --> 39:02.047
♪

39:02.173 --> 39:03.513
Well, then, um...

39:07.178 --> 39:10.508
I’ll just sit here a wee while,
if ye dinna mind.

39:10.598 --> 39:13.348
♪

39:13.434 --> 39:14.694
I dinna mind.

39:14.811 --> 39:17.691
♪

39:20.233 --> 39:23.243
[ chickens clucking ]

39:32.829 --> 39:35.369
[ birds chirping ]

39:48.553 --> 39:50.223
Do they hurt?

39:50.305 --> 39:53.315
Mine hurt from playing.

39:55.393 --> 39:57.063
They’re no’ bruises, lad.

39:58.563 --> 40:00.063
I chose them.

40:02.191 --> 40:04.861
Germain Fraser,
what are ye up to?

40:04.944 --> 40:06.614
I’m so sorry.

40:06.738 --> 40:08.028
Dinna mind.

40:09.365 --> 40:11.195
Sometimes it feels as though
I’m herding cats.

40:12.368 --> 40:13.738
Two bairns
is trouble enough,

40:13.870 --> 40:15.450
but wi’ another one
on the way...

40:15.580 --> 40:16.580
then keeping up
wi’ the gardening

40:16.706 --> 40:17.956
and the sewing

40:18.082 --> 40:20.082
and helping Claire
in the surgery,

40:20.168 --> 40:22.498
I’m at my wits’ end
before noon.

40:22.587 --> 40:25.087
[ sighs ]
Of course, I wouldna have it
any other way.

40:27.008 --> 40:30.138
Bairns are only lent to us
for a short time
by the Creator...

40:30.261 --> 40:31.641
if we’re lucky.

40:31.763 --> 40:34.603
[ birds chirping ]

40:37.769 --> 40:39.479
I suppose...

40:39.604 --> 40:41.444
[ exhales deeply ]

40:42.565 --> 40:45.775
Mine are lucky to have
wee brothers and sisters...

40:45.860 --> 40:47.110
like the Murrays.

40:49.948 --> 40:51.778
I only have a wee sister,
Joanie.

40:52.700 --> 40:57.040
She wasna as strong‐willed
as yer Janet,

40:57.121 --> 40:58.331
I recall.

40:59.624 --> 41:01.174
My sister always had
a mind of her own.

41:01.292 --> 41:02.592
[ laughs ]
Aye.

41:04.170 --> 41:06.130
She was a mischief‐maker.

41:11.636 --> 41:13.546
Tell the truth, I was always
a wee bit jealous...

41:15.890 --> 41:18.390
Wi’ only my ma and sister
for company at Balriggan.

41:23.815 --> 41:25.275
Ye must miss yer family.

41:33.282 --> 41:36.332
I do miss Ma and Joanie.

41:36.452 --> 41:39.412
Only....

41:39.497 --> 41:41.787
sometimes I feel guilty
about how happy I am here...

41:43.001 --> 41:44.961
And how I’ve...

41:45.044 --> 41:47.514
come to be at home
in this family.

41:50.675 --> 41:51.845
I feel I belong.

41:54.345 --> 41:55.545
Is that terrible?

41:57.098 --> 41:58.218
No.

41:59.392 --> 42:00.812
’Tis a good thing.

42:04.689 --> 42:05.559
[ laughs ]

42:09.360 --> 42:12.450
[ inhales sharply ]

42:12.530 --> 42:13.860
[ laughs ]

42:15.491 --> 42:17.621
Bairn’s kicking.
[ laughs ]

42:19.245 --> 42:20.865
He’ll be joining us
before too long.

42:22.165 --> 42:24.125
[ sighs ]

42:24.208 --> 42:28.588
I’m glad ye’ll be here
to welcome him...or her.

42:31.382 --> 42:33.132
[ melancholy music ]

42:33.217 --> 42:35.087
[ exhales deeply ]

42:35.219 --> 42:38.259
♪

42:51.903 --> 42:53.573
[ Marsali laughs ]

42:56.074 --> 42:58.744
BRIANNA:
I’m so glad Ian is going
with you on the survey.

42:59.786 --> 43:02.286
Before you leave, I wanted
to give you something.

43:03.623 --> 43:07.333
You told me that
you had a toy airplane

43:07.418 --> 43:08.788
when you were a boy.

43:10.588 --> 43:12.418
I didn’t get to finish
my degree,

43:12.548 --> 43:16.428
but I do know a little
something about aerodynamics.

43:16.552 --> 43:19.682
I know that
a sheet of paper

43:19.764 --> 43:22.314
is not made to fly,

43:22.433 --> 43:24.733
but sometimes we have to...

43:24.811 --> 43:27.901
adjust our expectations

43:27.980 --> 43:31.400
to bend and reshape ourselves.

43:33.111 --> 43:37.531
There’s a reason that
the first wedding anniversary
gift is supposed to be paper.

43:39.033 --> 43:43.453
And after the pressures
of 60 years, it’s diamond,

43:43.538 --> 43:45.288
the hardest substance on Earth.

43:47.667 --> 43:50.287
I want our marriage to grow
into something that strong.

43:52.338 --> 43:56.298
I love you...Roger Mac.

44:04.809 --> 44:05.889
[ door clicks shut ]

44:27.206 --> 44:30.076
[ solemn music ]

44:30.168 --> 44:33.048
♪

44:44.974 --> 44:47.854
[ upbeat music ]

44:47.935 --> 44:50.845
♪

44:59.864 --> 45:01.034
[ Rollo barks ]

45:01.157 --> 45:04.027
♪

45:14.045 --> 45:15.135
YOUNG IAN:
24.

45:15.213 --> 45:18.383
♪

45:28.142 --> 45:30.772
Ye dinna need to thank me.

45:30.895 --> 45:32.275
I came on my own.

45:32.396 --> 45:35.436
♪

46:07.890 --> 46:09.810
Did Brianna
no’ give this to ye?

46:09.934 --> 46:12.734
[ soft music ]

46:12.812 --> 46:14.272
♪

46:14.355 --> 46:15.775
Ye trust me not to break it?

46:15.898 --> 46:18.818
♪

46:39.130 --> 46:40.130
CLAIRE:
Marsali.

46:40.256 --> 46:42.926
♪

46:43.009 --> 46:45.139
Have you prescribed anyone
some water hemlock?

46:45.219 --> 46:46.469
No.
Why?

46:46.595 --> 46:47.505
It’s just,
there’s some missing.

46:47.638 --> 46:48.848
There’s only one root left.

46:48.973 --> 46:50.273
I thought maybe
you prescribed it

46:50.349 --> 46:51.679
to someone for a migraine or‐‐

46:51.809 --> 46:53.479
I wouldna touch the stuff,
being wi’ child.

46:53.602 --> 46:56.272
Yeah, that’s what I thought.

46:56.355 --> 46:58.065
It’s just, it’s so dangerous.

46:58.149 --> 47:00.779
I could have sworn we had
at least four or five pieces
of the root left.

47:00.860 --> 47:03.780
♪

47:08.034 --> 47:09.084
What’s that?

47:21.505 --> 47:22.875
A paper bird?

47:29.263 --> 47:30.563
[ Rollo whines ]

47:32.350 --> 47:33.680
[ Rollo growls ]

47:33.768 --> 47:37.438
It flies but doesna sing.

47:37.521 --> 47:40.361
[ somber music ]

47:40.483 --> 47:42.283
Couldna always understand
the Mohawk.

47:42.360 --> 47:44.400
♪

47:44.528 --> 47:47.408
Sometimes I’d talk
to the birds instead...

47:47.531 --> 47:49.201
so I didna feel so alone.

47:49.325 --> 47:52.205
♪

47:56.540 --> 47:58.080
Do ye ever wonder

47:58.209 --> 48:00.789
how they ken which way to go
when winter comes?

48:02.588 --> 48:04.918
And they always seem to...

48:05.049 --> 48:06.429
they always seem
to go together.

48:06.550 --> 48:08.640
♪

48:08.719 --> 48:10.759
Wish it was as easy
for us as well.

48:10.888 --> 48:13.598
♪

48:13.724 --> 48:16.234
[ bird calling ]

48:16.310 --> 48:17.980
[ whistling ]

48:18.062 --> 48:20.482
♪

48:20.564 --> 48:22.984
[ birds calling ]

48:23.067 --> 48:25.987
♪

48:27.488 --> 48:30.948
[ projector whirring ]

48:31.075 --> 48:33.875
[ ominous music ]

48:36.080 --> 48:38.250
[ sharp bang ]

48:38.374 --> 48:39.584
[ breathing heavily ]

48:49.218 --> 48:50.138
[ clears throat ]

48:51.345 --> 48:52.545
Were ye dreaming?

48:58.853 --> 49:01.063
[ astrolabe jingles ]

49:08.821 --> 49:11.111
Wherever you thought
you were,

49:11.198 --> 49:12.868
we’re both still here.

49:27.381 --> 49:28.631
[ cat meows ]

49:31.218 --> 49:32.218
Jamie.

49:33.804 --> 49:35.144
Do you think
there’s a chance

49:35.222 --> 49:37.142
that Roger might not want
to come home?

49:38.851 --> 49:39.811
Why?

49:42.229 --> 49:44.979
There are some herbs missing
from my surgery

49:45.107 --> 49:48.687
that are incredibly poisonous
unless administered correctly
by a physician.

49:49.570 --> 49:51.320
I worry that he might...

49:54.074 --> 49:58.254
Well...when you were suffering

49:58.329 --> 49:59.659
all those years ago...

50:01.957 --> 50:03.667
I didna want
to go on living.

50:07.379 --> 50:10.169
[ desolate music ]

50:10.257 --> 50:13.177
♪

50:36.617 --> 50:37.827
[ inhales sharply ]

50:37.910 --> 50:40.910
[ projector whirring ]

50:42.706 --> 50:44.536
Hang them and leave them
as an example to all.

50:44.625 --> 50:47.465
[ sinister music ]

50:47.545 --> 50:50.675
♪

50:54.635 --> 50:55.725
CHADWICK:
For your treasonous crimes,

50:55.844 --> 50:58.814
you’ll be hanged
by the neck until dead.

50:59.682 --> 51:01.892
May the Lord have mercy
on your souls.

51:05.771 --> 51:06.731
[ man grunts ]

51:06.855 --> 51:07.765
[ heartbeat thumping ]

51:07.898 --> 51:09.108
[ sharp bang ]

51:09.233 --> 51:12.493
[ Roger gagging ]

51:12.570 --> 51:15.410
[ heartbeat thumping ]

51:20.077 --> 51:22.407
[ gurgling ]

51:22.538 --> 51:25.458
[ rope squeaking ]

51:25.583 --> 51:28.093
[ heartbeat thumping ]

51:28.168 --> 51:30.128
[ gasps ]

51:30.254 --> 51:33.174
[ serene music ]

51:33.257 --> 51:34.627
[ exhales sharply ]

51:34.758 --> 51:37.838
♪

52:35.611 --> 52:38.241
[ Rollo whining ]

52:38.322 --> 52:41.372
♪

52:41.492 --> 52:42.992
[ whining continues ]

52:43.077 --> 52:44.407
[ Roger grunts softly ]

52:45.663 --> 52:48.503
[ whining continues ]

53:04.515 --> 53:07.275
[ suspenseful music ]

53:07.351 --> 53:10.271
♪

53:20.364 --> 53:23.204
[ dramatic music ]

53:23.325 --> 53:26.195
♪

53:51.854 --> 53:53.234
[ sniffles ]

53:56.567 --> 53:59.317
[ speaking Mohawk ]

54:07.035 --> 54:09.445
[ ominous drum
and flute music ]

54:09.580 --> 54:10.660
[ sniffles ]

54:10.748 --> 54:13.878
♪

54:56.460 --> 54:57.790
[ grunts ]
Why?

54:57.878 --> 55:00.128
Of all people,
why would ye stop me?

55:00.839 --> 55:02.219
I saw ye looking down
at the cliff.

55:02.299 --> 55:03.759
I ken what ye were thinking.

55:03.842 --> 55:06.092
Ye have everything:

55:06.178 --> 55:08.848
a wife that loves ye...

55:08.972 --> 55:11.682
a bairn...

55:11.809 --> 55:13.389
and still, ye dinna
wanna be wi’ them.

55:15.687 --> 55:17.357
When that rope
was around yer neck

55:17.481 --> 55:20.441
and ye were dying...

55:20.526 --> 55:21.526
what did ye see?

55:22.736 --> 55:24.146
[ grunts ]

55:24.279 --> 55:25.909
What did ye see
in the darkness?

55:25.989 --> 55:27.369
[ grunts ]

55:27.491 --> 55:29.081
What did ye see?

55:30.410 --> 55:33.000
Tell me, what did ye see?
[ grunts ]

55:38.836 --> 55:41.336
[ groans softly, croaks ]

55:43.841 --> 55:45.511
I saw my wife’s face.

55:51.056 --> 55:52.216
Then there’s no escape?

55:54.017 --> 55:56.727
Even in death,

55:56.854 --> 55:58.564
I would see her face?

55:58.689 --> 56:00.769
[ melancholy music ]

56:00.858 --> 56:02.358
What...

56:02.484 --> 56:04.694
♪

56:04.778 --> 56:06.358
What was her name?

56:06.488 --> 56:09.368
♪

56:13.620 --> 56:14.790
It doesna matter now.

56:14.872 --> 56:18.002
♪

56:26.425 --> 56:27.595
Is she dead?

56:27.718 --> 56:30.598
♪

56:32.764 --> 56:34.394
No.

56:34.516 --> 56:37.386
♪

56:39.563 --> 56:40.813
But she’s lost to me.

56:40.898 --> 56:44.028
♪

56:46.695 --> 56:48.365
I only wanted the pain to end.

56:48.447 --> 56:51.367
♪

56:52.701 --> 56:53.951
Just to be at peace.

56:54.077 --> 56:57.117
♪

57:01.501 --> 57:03.131
[ wheezes ]

57:08.675 --> 57:11.295
Who can say where your soul
might go if you...

57:16.058 --> 57:19.268
If you could be parted
forever...

57:19.353 --> 57:21.483
not only from her
but from all who love you.

57:21.605 --> 57:22.695
So what now?

57:24.399 --> 57:25.439
Go home?

57:26.944 --> 57:28.494
Ye’re a fine one to talk.

57:31.782 --> 57:35.622
Ye buried yer weapon,
yer voice.

57:36.286 --> 57:38.496
Now ye dare
to use it against me.

57:39.998 --> 57:42.628
Ye’re right.

57:42.709 --> 57:43.629
I did.

57:46.797 --> 57:49.127
But now I have
to pick it up again and fight.

57:50.968 --> 57:52.718
Can you?

57:57.766 --> 57:59.226
I dinna ken.

58:00.727 --> 58:02.477
Then dig up your weapon...

58:04.314 --> 58:06.444
And come home with me
until you do.

58:10.612 --> 58:13.492
♪

58:15.033 --> 58:18.123
[ Rollo barking ]

58:18.203 --> 58:21.003
[ uplifting music ]

58:21.081 --> 58:24.171
♪

58:31.675 --> 58:32.805
[ door clicks open ]

58:32.884 --> 58:35.854
♪

58:44.730 --> 58:46.520
Brianna.

58:51.194 --> 58:53.614
Don’t tell me you’re at
a loss for words now.

58:53.697 --> 58:54.657
No.

58:56.074 --> 58:58.744
No, it’s just...

58:58.869 --> 59:00.869
I have been so scared.

59:01.663 --> 59:02.543
Me too.

59:04.541 --> 59:08.341
Because even though
I was saved...

59:10.005 --> 59:12.305
Part of me died that day.

59:17.596 --> 59:19.716
[ whispering ]
I know how that feels.

59:19.848 --> 59:22.228
Trust me, I know.

59:29.691 --> 59:32.741
Everybody wants
the old Roger back.

59:38.992 --> 59:40.912
But I’ll never be
that man again.

59:43.997 --> 59:45.417
I studied history.

59:46.750 --> 59:47.880
I taught it.

59:49.252 --> 59:51.422
Now I’m living it.

59:52.631 --> 59:55.881
When I saw that tarot card,
I thought,

59:55.967 --> 59:58.387
"This is who I am now..."

1:00:01.306 --> 1:00:03.556
"The hanged man."

1:00:06.061 --> 1:00:08.441
Maybe this was my fate.

1:00:08.563 --> 1:00:12.533
My own ancestor
tried to kill me.

1:00:15.028 --> 1:00:17.108
Maybe I wasn’t meant
to exist.

1:00:17.197 --> 1:00:18.657
That is not true.

1:00:18.782 --> 1:00:19.822
Perhaps not.

1:00:21.284 --> 1:00:23.414
But I have changed.

1:00:26.414 --> 1:00:28.634
Remember when you asked me
about my last words?

1:00:30.794 --> 1:00:31.674
[ softly ]
Yeah.

1:00:31.795 --> 1:00:34.555
I thought I knew
what they’d be.

1:00:36.133 --> 1:00:39.893
What mattered
was the last face I saw.

1:00:44.558 --> 1:00:47.228
[ sniffles ]
That face was yours.

1:00:47.310 --> 1:00:50.270
[ warm music ]

1:00:50.355 --> 1:00:52.185
[ sighs ]
Roger.

1:00:52.315 --> 1:00:55.435
♪

1:01:03.869 --> 1:01:05.699
I’ll always sing for you.

1:01:07.414 --> 1:01:09.834
No matter what,
no matter where...

1:01:09.916 --> 1:01:12.376
♪

1:01:12.502 --> 1:01:13.962
Whether you’re there to hear

1:01:14.045 --> 1:01:17.005
or even if my voice
isn’t able...

1:01:17.090 --> 1:01:20.550
I will always sing for you.

1:01:20.677 --> 1:01:23.597
♪

